      <description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;hr&gt;Iceblossom wrote:&lt;br&gt;&#xD;
&lt;p&gt;While I have mentioned the changing in tiers in other posts I had&#xD;
forgotten about it.&amp;nbsp; So, ok, foraging was looked at during the velious&#xD;
era because the change (as I recall) was pre-luclin.&lt;/p&gt;&#xD;
&lt;p&gt;Still a long time ago.&lt;/p&gt;&#xD;
&lt;p&gt;And&amp;nbsp;you made my point very nicely on how even if you gave everyone&#xD;
50 forage it would not be game breaking or class breaking.&amp;nbsp; But it&#xD;
would give people who want to do things themselves the ability to go&#xD;
somewhere and forage for 16 hours if that is what they wanted to do.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;The&#xD;
point is that it HAS been looked at, and there is no evidence that it&#xD;
hasn't been looked at since. A lack of changes does not mean that it&#xD;
hasn't been looked at. A lack of changes only means that it hasn't been&#xD;
changed (trite but true). Yes it could mean that it hasn't been&#xD;
looked at, it could also mean that it has been looked at and no changes&#xD;
were needed.&lt;br&gt;&#xD;
&lt;br&gt;&#xD;
&lt;br&gt;&#xD;
Are you saying they should be allowed to forage simply because they&#xD;
want to do things for themselves? Does this mean I should be able to&#xD;
enchant silver bars because I want to get to 300 in jewelcrafting&#xD;
myself without the aid of others? Enchanted silver would not be game or&#xD;
class breaking, after all the enchanters do have other functions&#xD;
besides enchanting metal and probably would be quite happy if I quit&#xD;
running up to them asking them to enchant 100 stacks of silver for me.&#xD;
How about I be given the ability to embue emeralds because I want to&#xD;
get smithing to 300 and want to do it myself. Again druids have other&#xD;
functions besides embuing rocks so it wouldn't be class breaking. Since&#xD;
I am a Tunare worshipper it wouldn't be game breaking. I could even&#xD;
come up with a lame lore reason for me embuing emeralds. Not only am I&#xD;
a Tunare worshipper but I am a ranger making me partially a druid. I grew up with&#xD;
druids in Surefall Glade. The Druid GM's like me just as much as the&#xD;
Ranger GM's, why wouldn't they teach a few select high level rangers to&#xD;
embue emeralds?&lt;br&gt;&#xD;
&lt;br&gt;&#xD;
I have read one person advocating gutting forage. Only food and drink&#xD;
could be foraged. Anything with a tradeskill tag would be removed from&#xD;
the forage table. Anything of any value would be removed from the&#xD;
forage table. The person that advocated this evidently is just mean&#xD;
spirited or is clueless as to what is on the forage tables. (Hint:&#xD;
Almost 100% of the food and drink items on the forage tables have a&#xD;
tradeskill tags.)&lt;br&gt;&#xD;
&lt;br&gt;&#xD;
There has been arguements that granting forage to everyone (even with a&#xD;
skill limit of 50) would just make things convenient. Why not just&#xD;
advocate putting Tradeskill vendors in the PoK with all the tradeskill&#xD;
items on them.&amp;nbsp; Oh.. wait... we had that for a while. Oddly it was the&#xD;
tradeskillers themselves that made a stink about it. The final results&#xD;
of that little unintended experiment were, shall we say, less than&#xD;
desireable.&lt;br&gt;&#xD;
&lt;br&gt;&#xD;
There have been arguements based on lore for extending forage to&#xD;
everyone. Most of these arguements are based on a mixture EQ lore and&#xD;
outside lore. I am sorry but if you wish to use lore as an argument you&#xD;
have to base it on EQ lore alone. What happens in middle-earth, what&#xD;
the pioneers did in their movement west in the new world, etc. has no&#xD;
relationship to EverQuest. Nowhere in EQ lore does it state that even a&#xD;
single DE enchanter (or any other race/class combination that didn't&#xD;
have forage), even an extraordinary one, ever foraged anything.&lt;br&gt;&#xD;
&lt;br&gt;&#xD;
I have seen attempts at logic used to explain why foraging should be&#xD;
extended to everyone. This simplest of these is basically anyone can be&#xD;
taught to forage in the real world (we will ignore this attempt to mix&#xD;
real world with EverQuest) even those of limited intelligence.&#xD;
Logically any player race or class that is capable of learning (and&#xD;
they all are) should be able to forage because it is, after all, a&#xD;
learned skill. Well let see. We have a world that really doesn't exist&#xD;
except in the imagination of the players. That world has an entire&#xD;
pantheon of dieties that on whim interfere with the mortal world. We&#xD;
have mortals that can kill those dieties and in many cases with ease.&#xD;
We have magic that can both work with and bend the laws of nature. The&#xD;
player races have no children, the gnolls and orcs should have taken&#xD;
over long ago. When you die, it isn't over. Yep, it is easy to see that&#xD;
Logic is the dominant force in EverQuest.&lt;br&gt;&#xD;
&lt;br&gt;&#xD;
So far the best arguement for extending foraging to everyone is quest&#xD;
related. The problem is the solution of extending foraging is entirely&#xD;
bass ackwards. Foraging doesn't need fixing, the quests need fixing.&#xD;
Change the quests so they don't require foraging (the race/class&#xD;
non-specific quests).&lt;br&gt;&#xD;
&lt;br&gt;&#xD;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&#xD;
