    <item>
      <title>Re: Forage vs Drops.</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=Trade&amp;message.id=14402#M14402</link>
      <description>&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;Well, like with Vegeta-X we will just have to disagree what we see as the fundamental points of the argument.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;But once again:&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;No, I am not in favor of all classes being the same.&amp;nbsp; However, with the blurring of races and classes that can forage, I don't feel the differences are as definitive as you apparently believe them to be.&amp;nbsp; If it was ONLY iksars for example, or ONLY rangers and druids, I would see the point more clearly.&amp;nbsp; But with all&amp;nbsp;Druids, all Rangers, all Bards, all Wood Elves and all Iksars I simply don't see it as an especially class defining ability, I do see it more in line with swimming.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;I've always said that I can accept forage staying the way it is.&amp;nbsp; I still believe that with the greater number of races and classes that are now in the game, it should be looked at, for example perhaps beastlords should have forage.&amp;nbsp; Maybe it has been looked at, maybe it hasn't.&amp;nbsp; At this point we don't know.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;My prefered solution is that the sloppy itemization and coding should be fixed.&amp;nbsp; That would include quests with no drop foraged components have the results correctly tagged.&amp;nbsp; As I've used before, if the final product is tagged Cleric, Druid, Shaman wearable then a cleric should be able to get the result and there are no clerics, zip, nada, none that can forage.&amp;nbsp; Same thing goes for other items, while I guess it is harmless, why should a warrior have a warrior only weapon that includes mana?&amp;nbsp; Answer is it is easier to copy something and give it a new name than it is to copy it, give it a new name, and take the mana off.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;To go through all the thousands of items and quests and all that to fix the sloppy stuff would take considerable time away from doing other, yes, more important&amp;nbsp;things.&amp;nbsp; To give everybody forage (which I usually preface with "even if") is probably easier and faster than fixing stuff.&amp;nbsp; While I don't believe that a sloppy solution is the best recourse for a sloppy problem, it is an option.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;When I do talk about "even if everyone had forage" I am talking about a 50 skill, and it would preferably be a skill that had to be trained up 50 and not just set at 50 (although for programming sake, whatever's easier...).&amp;nbsp; Maybe to even things out, wood elves and iksars would be able to skill up/train to 100 or 75 or something.&amp;nbsp; Druids and Rangers would still have the clear advantage, that lorewise they do have superior abilities in this area would not be changed.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;The reality is, most people are not going to do much with a 50 skill.&amp;nbsp; Most people probably won't bother with it any more than they do their swimming skill.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;It provides a sloppy fix to a sloppy problem and does not take away anything from anyone.&lt;/P&gt;</description>
